Press conference with the Scientific Committee, headed by the Minister of Health - 20 Apr 2014
-----------------------
The Minister of Health Dr. Abdullah Al rabi'a revealed there were 13 new cases of MERS Co-V confirmed, including 7 cases in Jeddah, 4 in Riyadh, one in Al Madina Al Monawwarah and one in Najran, bringing the total number of laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection in the Kingdom to 244. The Minister assured [the public] that the ministry is working as hard as it could to contain the virus, giving assurances that the ministry is read for the Hajj and Umrah seasons with what it has of wide experiences as it became a scientific reference in mass gathering health issues.

This was revealed during a press conference the Minister held this afternoon [20 Apr 2014] with the presence of members of the National Scientific committee of infectious diseases[NSCID], and the national committees for fighting infections. The minister announced that the NSCID assured that the procedures currently undertaken in the health facilities are according to international and national standards for infection fighting [control], and there is no need for any additions for preparation as all tools and supplies are available to deal with cases.

The Minister addressed concerns by stating that no cases have been found at schools, which he considered a very positive sign, and that the reported cases among healthcare workers are in decline, as is mortality rates - which decreased from 60 percent at the beginning of the emergence of the virus to 35 percent last week, to 32 percent today [20 Apr 2014].

The Minister projects an increase in the number of confirmed cases in the coming few weeks as a result of the epidemiological investigations. The Minister indicated that 20 000 individuals have been tested for MERS-CoV, showing the magnitude of the work the Ministry is doing. The minister announced that the NSCID, and with the vote of all its members - who represent most of the country's Ministries and Health Sectors as well as private sector - will conduct a daily meeting to be continuously updated about the virus.

The Minister indicated that the ministry invited 22 experts from the WHO and Centers for Disease Control in Europe, America and East Asia, as well as experts from the Gulf region cooperation council to meet at the end of this week at the Ministry of Health headquarters to review these cases and come up with new recommendations. The Ministry also invited national and international experts as well as 5 international vaccine manufacturing companies to meet with the Ministry of Health to investigate possibilities to find a vaccine with the information currently known about the virus.

The NSCID mentioned that total number of cases confirmed in the province of Jeddah has reached 64, including 12 deaths bringing the case fatality rate in Jeddah to 18 percent and the overall mortality due to MERS-CoV infection in the Kingdom to 32 percent.

The committee also announced the total numbers of cases in the following health sectors: Defence Ministries, National Guard, Interior, Health and the Private Sector, University Hospitals and Saudi Aramco:
- MOH hospitals 103 cases,
- Ministry of Defence 46 cases
- National Guard Hospitals 30 cases
- Public Security Forces Hospitals 6 cases
- University Hospital 6 cases
- Aramco 14 cases
- Private Sector Hospitals 26 cases
- King Faisal Specialized Hospitals in Riyadh and Jeddah 13 cases

and this is since the 1st detection of the disease back in 2012, bringing the total to 244 cases, noting that the cases in the MOH hospitals includes patients and people who interacted with cases ["contacts"] whether they were in MOH hospitals or not.

The Minster stressed to the Committee that he and the MOH will provide all members of the community, the media and social networking guidelines of health and medical advice on the MERS-CoV and inform them of the developments in this field. They invite everyone to access the link on the disease through the Ministry's website <www.moh.gov.sa / coronanew>, or communicate via toll-free phone 800 249 4444 or center 937, or by contacting the Ministry in Twitter saudimoh @, and wish for all health and safety.

The Minister also mentioned that some of the allegations of medical in finding a cure for the disease or eliminate the virus in ambulances the committee said that there is no scientific evidence for this information. The SCNID confirmed that there was no vaccine or preventive treatment as yet, and as yet the source of contagion s unknown, and it is not as yet known how infection is transmitted from one person to another. The research is still ongoing with regard to the basic knowledge on the source of infection. Samples have been taken in several regions of the Kingdom and results are still pending.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As mentioned above, the total global tally of laboratory confirmed MERS-CoV infections is now over 300. Noteworthy is that according to the line listing of reported laboratory confirmed cases of MERS-CoV infection this moderator has been keeping, there have been a total of 95 new cases reported since 1 Apr 2014 (over a 3 week period), including 17 deaths. Cases have been reported by Saudi Arabia, UAE, Jordan, Malaysia and Greece and one from Yemen that has not as yet been confirmed by official sources outside of media reports. During this period there has been an ongoing outbreak in hospital(s) in Jeddah Saudi Arabia (64 cases including 12 deaths, ongoing diagnoses of cases in Riyadh (16 cases including 2 deaths) with no apparent clustering (from limited information that is available) as well as 14 individuals in the UAE who had known contact with a single healthcare worker who died of MERS-CoV associated illness. In contrast, in April 2013 there were no cases report, but in May 2013 there was the nosocomial outbreak(s) in the Eastern Province, with 28 cases including 15 deaths. There is the suggestion of possible seasonality, but no confirmation of that. What awaits to be seen is whether this apparent "explosion" in the numbers of cases of MERS-CoV infection this month (April 2014) is a result of either a change in the virus itself with enhanced numbers of human infections, the appearance of superspreaders contributing to the increased transmission of virus between contacts, or perhaps more a function of the adage "seek and ye shall find", and there is more active surveillance ongoing now than previously. One suspects there is quite possibly a mix of all these possibilities contributing to the observed major increase in MERS-CoV infections. - Mod.MPP]
